================================================================================
Relationship to Berkeley DB Java Edition (provenance)
================================================================================

Noxu DB's value proposition is fidelity to BDB JE's design. Its public API,
engine architecture, algorithms, method structure, and much of its documented
behavior deliberately track JE 7.5.11. To make the provenance explicit:

  * Translated from JE source structure: the algorithm shapes, method
    decomposition, invariants, and many doc-comment contents of the core engine
    (log/file manager, IN/BIN/LN tree with key prefixing and BIN-deltas,
    evictor with memory budget, cleaner with per-file utilization,
    checkpoint-based multi-phase recovery, record-level lock manager with
    deadlock detection) follow JE's Java expression closely. Where Noxu code
    corresponds to a JE site, the source method is cited in comments.

  * Reimplemented from JE documentation / behavior (not line-for-line): the
    public API surface (Environment / Database / Cursor / Transaction, the
    operation-based Get/Put model, secondary databases, join/disk-ordered
    cursors, sequences, DPL persistence, collections bindings) mirrors JE's
    documented contracts.

  * Original to Noxu (not derived from JE): the on-disk log format (`.ndb`),
    the internal sync primitives (`noxu-sync`), memory-mapped log I/O, the
    replication transport and election protocol (Flexible Paxos, Phi Accrual
    failure detection, QUIC/rustls), the executable Stateright protocol
    specifications, the observability stack, and the additional cache-eviction
    policies (CLOCK / LIRS / ARC / CAR). These carry no inherited JE hardening.

